Barbados was first resettled by Amerindians around 3500 BC. They are thought to have migrated in two waves. The first wave consisted of members of the Ortoiroid people, from Venezuela’s Orinoco River area. They arrived first. The second wave consisted of members of the Saladoid people from mainland South America. They arrived a century later and supplanted the Ortoiroids. Barbadians trace part of their genealogy to Bush Indians, descendants of settlers who originally came from the Orinoco area of South America.

The History of Barbados is pretty cool too. Barbados is the easternmost island in the Caribbean. It shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican Republic to the west and Haiti. Barbados’ sugar plantations became full of African slaves when Africa’s inhabitants were first used to dislodge successful indigenous inhabitants. When slavery ended here most Portuguese immigrants intermarried with the remaining slave population.

The Brits colonized it in 1627 and have held on to it since. A 1674 rebellion ripped “Whittox”, a long time cult leader, from the hands of the Brits and Pirates became the new power in Barbados.
